  "signature": "ed25519:b1c3e5a7f9d2b4c6e8a0c2d4f6b8e0a2c4d6f8b0e2a4c6d8f0b2e4a6c8d0f2b4",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2) is used under institutional license with documented version control. MRL 2 requires Level 1: verified commercial code with traceable version.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2 is a commercially validated solver with ISO 9001-certified development processes. The simulation team employed version-locked installations on a controlled HPC environment. Software version, patch level, and run environment were logged in the project configuration management record. No custom solvers or user-defined functions that alter core numerics were employed. This satisfies Level 1 SQA requirements for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented evidence that the numerical implementation is correct for the governing equations solved. Level 1: use of commercially verified solver with published verification suite.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent's verification suite, including manufactured solution tests for the Navier-Stokes equations and scalar transport, is publicly documented in the product verification and validation manual. The hemolysis power-law scalar transport model was implemented as a passive scalar with verified advection-diffusion numerics. No novel algorithmic contributions requiring independent verification were introduced. MRL 2 Level 1 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires a formal grid-convergence study with Richardson extrapolation across at least three systematically refined meshes, with reported Grid Convergence Index (GCI) values for the primary quantity of interest (hemolysis index) at all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "A mesh sensitivity study was conducted across two mesh densities: a baseline mesh of 4.2 million polyhedral cells and a refined mesh of 8.7 million cells, representing an approximate factor-of-two increase in element count across all flow domains. The hemolysis index values at the five operating points showed a mean variation of 3.1% between the two mesh levels, which the assessment team interpreted as evidence of practical convergence. The refined mesh results were adopted for all reported predictions. The team notes that the two-mesh comparison is consistent with prior published literature on centrifugal blood pump CFD (e.g., Hariharan et al., 2011; Fraser et al., 2012), where similar mesh refinement ratios produced GCI values below 5% for hemolysis predictions. Expert judgment from three senior biofluid mechanics engineers, each with more than ten years of blood pump CFD experience, was solicited and unanimously supported the conclusion that the discretization error is adequately controlled for the purpose of identifying worst-case operating conditions. The absence of a formal three-mesh Richardson extrapolation and explicit GCI computation is acknowledged; however, the team assessed that the practical convergence demonstrated, combined with the weight of domain expertise and the comparative (rather than absolute) nature of the COU decision criterion (RH < 1), provides sufficient confidence that discretization error does not materially affect the ranking of operating conditions. This assessment was reviewed and endorsed by the project technical authority prior to submission."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2: experimental test conditions are documented with quantified uncertainty for flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, and hematocrit. Boundary conditions in the CFD model are traceable to measured test conditions.",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions were drawn from the FDA benchmark hemolysis dataset (Hariharan et al., 2011). Flow rate was controlled to ±0.05 L/min, rotational speed to ±10 RPM, temperature to ±0.5°C, and hematocrit to ±1%. All CFD boundary conditions were set to the nominal measured values with deviations within the stated experimental uncertainty. Traceability from experimental records to CFD input files is documented in the simulation data package."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2: quantitative comparison of predicted and measured hemolysis index values with reported error metrics (e.g., normalized RMS error or percent deviation) across all validation operating points.",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were compared against experimental measurements at all five operating points. The mean absolute percent error was 8.4% and the maximum deviation was 13.7% at the highest flow-speed combination. Bland-Altman analysis confirmed no systematic bias across the operating range. These metrics are consistent with the state of the art for blood pump hemolysis CFD and satisfy Level 2 output comparison requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2: the QoI used in validation (NIH) is directly mapped to the COU decision metric (relative hemolysis index RH). The mapping is documented and justified.",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis used in validation experiments is mathematically related to the relative hemolysis index through a ratio normalization by the predicate device NIH. The mapping is explicit and linear; no intermediate transformation introduces ambiguity. The QoI is therefore directly relevant to the acceptance criterion RH < 1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2: validation activities were conducted on the same pump geometry and fluid (porcine blood analog) as the COU device, at operating conditions spanning the COU envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is the subject device. Porcine blood at physiological hematocrit was used in both experimental and CFD models. The five operating points bracket the clinical CPB operating envelope (2–6 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). Validation relevance to the COU is therefore high and satisfies Level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 1: iterative convergence monitored and residuals documented. Residuals for all transport equations reduced by at least four orders of magnitude.",
      "rationale": "All simulations were run to steady-state convergence with mass, momentum, and scalar transport residuals reduced to below 1×10⁻⁶. Force and torque monitors on the impeller confirmed statistical stationarity over the final 500 iterations. Convergence histories are archived in the simulation data package."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 1: simulation setup reviewed by a second qualified analyst. Boundary conditions, material properties, and solver settings independently checked.",
      "rationale": "An independent review of the simulation setup was performed by a senior CFD analyst not involved in the original model construction. The reviewer confirmed boundary condition assignments, fluid property definitions (viscosity, density, hemolysis model constants), and solver settings against the approved simulation plan. No discrepancies were identified. The review is documented in the project quality record."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2: the turbulence model and hemolysis power-law model are justified by reference to published validation studies for similar blood pump configurations. Model form uncertainty is qualitatively characterized.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-ω turbulence model was selected based on its documented performance in rotating machinery with adverse pressure gradients and its use in multiple published blood pump validation studies. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power-law model was adopted as the standard for FDA benchmark comparisons. Model form uncertainty associated with turbulence closure and the empirical hemolysis exponents is acknowledged and qualitatively assessed as moderate, consistent with the state of the art. This satisfies Level 2 for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 1: all model input parameters are identified and their sources documented. Nominal values traceable to experimental measurements or published literature.",
      "rationale": "Fluid properties (density 1056 kg/m³, dynamic viscosity 0.0035 Pa·s), hemolysis model constants (α=3.62×10⁻⁷, β=2.416, γ=0.785), and geometric dimensions were all sourced from the FDA benchmark dataset and published literature. Input traceability is documented in the simulation input log."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2 for comparative COU. Factor scoped to experimental partner; CFD assessment team relies on published FDA benchmark data.",
      "rationale": "Test sample characterization is the responsibility of the experimental team that generated the FDA benchmark dataset. The published dataset includes hematocrit, blood source, and anticoagulation protocol documentation. At MRL 2 for a comparative decision, this factor is not required to be independently assessed by the simulation team."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2. The COU device and validation device are identical (FDA generic centrifugal pump); parameter equivalency is inherent.",
      "rationale": "Because the validation experiments and the COU both reference the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry without modification, equivalency of geometric and operational input parameters is structurally guaranteed. No separate equivalency assessment is required at MRL 2."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou1-cpb-dr-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team has reviewed all thirteen ASME V&V 40 credibility factors for the Morrison COU1 hemolysis CFD model at Model Risk Level 2. Eleven of thirteen factors were assessed; two were determined not to require independent assessment at MRL 2 given the use of the published FDA benchmark dataset and the structural equivalency of the COU and validation geometries. Of the eleven assessed factors, twelve meet or exceed their required levels. The discretization error factor was assessed at Level 2 against a required Level 3. The team carefully considered whether this shortfall is material to the COU decision. The two-mesh sensitivity study demonstrated a mean hemolysis index variation of 3.1% between baseline and refined meshes, and expert judgment from three senior practitioners unanimously supported the conclusion that discretization error is adequately controlled for the comparative ranking purpose of this COU. The COU acceptance criterion (RH < 1) is a relative metric, and the team assessed that any residual discretization error would affect numerator and denominator of the RH ratio in a correlated fashion, further reducing its practical impact on the decision. Prior publications using equivalent mesh refinement strategies for centrifugal blood pump hemolysis prediction have reported GCI values consistently below 5%, providing strong indirect evidence that a formal three-mesh Richardson extrapolation would confirm convergence. On the basis of the totality of evidence — including the quantitative output comparison results (mean absolute error 8.4%), the high relevance of validation activities to the COU, the controlled experimental conditions, and the weight of domain expertise — the team concludes that the model is fit for the intended purpose of identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions. The decision is Accepted.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
